 /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As you can see, no more JS thread and no more bridge which means faster animations! 🎉🎉</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><a href=\"https://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2017/02/14/using-native-driver-for-animated#how-do-i-use-this-in-my-app\"></a>How do I use this in my app?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For normal animations the answer is simple, just add&nbsp;<code>useNativeDriver: true</code>&nbsp;to the animation config when starting it.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Animated.timing(this.state.animatedValue, {\n  toValue: 1,\n  duration: 500,\n}).start();\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>Animated.timing(this.state.animatedValue, {\n  toValue: 1,\n  duration: 500,\n  useNativeDriver: true, // &lt;-- Add this\n}).start();\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Animated values are only compatible with one driver so if you use native driver when starting an animation on a value, make sure every animation on that value also uses the native driver.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It also works with&nbsp;<code>Animated.event</code>, this is very useful if you have an animation that must follow the scroll position because without the native driver it will always run a frame behind of the gesture because of the async nature of React Native.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;ScrollView\n  scrollEventThrottle={16}\n  onScroll={Animated.event(\n    [{ nativeEvent: { contentOffset: { y: this.state.animatedValue } } }]\n  )}\n>\n  {content}\n&lt;/ScrollView>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:code -->\n<pre class=\"wp-block-code\"><code>&lt;Animated.ScrollView // &lt;-- Use the Animated ScrollView wrapper\n  scrollEventThrottle={1} // &lt;-- Use 1 here to make sure no events are ever missed\n  onScroll={Animated.event(\n    [{ nativeEvent: { contentOffset: { y: this.state.animatedValue } } }],\n    { useNativeDriver: true } // &lt;-- Add this\n  )}\n>\n  {content}\n&lt;/Animated.ScrollView>\n</code></pre>\n<!-- /wp:code -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><a href=\"https://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2017/02/14/using-native-driver-for-animated#caveats\"></a>Caveats</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Not everything you can do with Animated is currently supported in Native Animated. The main limitation is that you can only animate non-layout properties, things like&nbsp;<code>transform</code>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<code>opacity</code>&nbsp;will work but flexbox and position properties won\'t. Another one is with&nbsp;<code>Animated.event</code>, it will only work with direct events and not bubbling events. This means it does not work with&nbsp;<code>PanResponder</code>&nbsp;but does work with things like&nbsp;<code>ScrollView#onScroll</code>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Native Animated has also been part of React Native for quite a while but has never been documented because it was considered experimental. Because of that make sure you are using a recent version (0.40+) of React Native if you want to use this feature.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2><a href=\"https://facebook.github.io/react-native/blog/2017/02/14/using-native-driver-for-animated#resources\"></a>Resources</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For more information about animated I recommend watching&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xtqUJVqpKNo\">this talk</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://twitter.com/Vjeux\">Christopher Chedeau</a>.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>If you want a deep dive into animations and how offloading them to native can improve user experience there is also&nbsp;<a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qgSMjYWqBk4\">this talk</a>&nbsp;by&nbsp;<a href=\"https://twitter.com/kzzzf\">Krzysztof Magiera</a>.<br></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Using Native Driver for Animated', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '92-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-05-30 14:01:15', '2019-05-30 14:01:15', '', 92, 'http://localhost/wordpress-portfolio/wordpress-portfolio/2019/05/30/92-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
