(97, 1, '2019-05-30 14:07:56', '2019-05-30 14:07:56', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The goal for this project is to explore with CSS Grid, CSS Flexbox, and CSS Floats as they pertain to website layout. In this project, we will create a website that looks like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image\"><img src=\"https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1200/1*COW8srUCa0W5pH7AUzhT1Q.jpeg\" alt=\"\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When the browser window reaches a certain width, you’ll see the layout like in the picture on the left. Where the “section” is on top of the “article,” but the “aside” is to the right of both the “section” and the “article.”</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Once this width is reached, all of the elements will be stacked on top of each other.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For example: when your web browser reaches a certain width, all of the elements will be stacked on top of each other in this order: header, nav, section, article, aside, and footer.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>You can use CSS Grid, CSS Flexbox or CSS Floats to achieve this. You can use a combination of all three, or you can attempt this layout in each — creating three different websites.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Any other styling or any other changes to the content are entirely up to you.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Again, of course, the website must be responsive, and your HTML must be semantic.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Project 2 — The Grid / Flexbox / Floats Project', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'project-2%e2%80%8a-%e2%80%8athe-grid-flexbox-floats-project', '', '', '2019-05-31 16:55:43', '2019-05-31 16:55:43', '', 0, 'http://localhost/wordpress-portfolio/wordpress-portfolio/?p=97', 0, 'post', '', 0),
